questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Antigen presenting cells are only available when a person is sick.
questions.explanation: False. Antigen-presenting cells (APCs) are constantly circulating throughout the body, sampling for pathogens, even when a person is healthy.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: An antigen presenting cell carries an antigen with it to present it to a helper T cell.
questions.explanation: True. This is the fundamental role of an antigen-presenting cell: to process and present antigens to helper T cells to initiate an adaptive immune response.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: The antigen presenting cells make antibodies.
questions.explanation: False. Antibodies are produced by plasma cells, which are differentiated B cells. Antigen-presenting cells activate T cells, which in turn help activate B cells.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: In Type I diabetes, the cells of the body actually attack the pancreas, confusing it with proteins similar to those found on the surface of milk proteins.
questions.explanation: True. This is a leading hypothesis known as molecular mimicry, where the immune system mistakenly targets the insulin-producing cells of the pancreas due to their resemblance to a foreign protein, like one from cow's milk.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Celiac disease occurs when the sequences of wheat, the small intestine and the virus Adeno-12 are confused.
questions.explanation: True. This is another example of molecular mimicry, where similarities between a protein in wheat (gluten), a human protein, and a viral protein (from adenovirus 12) can trigger an autoimmune reaction against the small intestine in susceptible individuals.
